{
  "text": "In addition to these physical forces, proteolytic factors also affect plaque stability. An infiltration of inflammatory cells is a common feature of disrupted plaques, especially in the \"shoulder regions\" (Lendon et al, 1991; [CITATION_1] . These inflammatory cells, primarily macrophages, express zymogen forms of matrix metalloproteinases (MMP) that, when activated, degrade the collagen and elastin components of the plaque [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Activated mast cells are also increased in vulnerable plaques and secrete enzymes such as tryptase and chymase that can activate pro-MMP derived from SMC and macrophages [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
